---
// "What is dynamic causality?" — below-the-fold plain-language explainer.
// Three short paragraphs, prose-measure constrained, no decorative imagery.
---
<section class="explainer">
  <div class="explainer-inner">
    <p class="eyebrow">What is dynamic causality</p>
    <h2>Causal reasoning that doesn&rsquo;t freeze the world.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Most causal-inference libraries assume a static graph and a fixed set of rules. Real systems
        rarely cooperate. A trading regime shifts; a robot enters a new room; a service mesh reroutes
        traffic. The variables stay the same; the relationships between them do not.
      </p>
      <p>
        DeepCausality treats causality as a spacetime-agnostic functional dependency. Causaloids
        encode each rule as a small composable unit. A Context hypergraph encodes the environment
        those rules operate in. The Effect Ethos verifies that whatever the rules conclude still
        satisfies the operational policies you have to honor.
      </p>
      <p>
        The framework is written in Rust, runs in real time, and stays correct when both the data
        and the rules evolve under it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .explainer {
    padding: var(--space-9) 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line-1);
  }
  .explainer-inner {
    max-width: var(--w-prose);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 var(--space-5);
    display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-4);
  }
  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--t-eyebrow); letter-spacing: var(--ls-eyebrow);
    text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--fg-2);
  }
  h2 { margin: 0 0 var(--space-3) 0; }
  .prose p { color: var(--fg-1); max-width: var(--measure); }
</style>
